y scholar, elocutionist, author, lecturer, inventor, and educational pioneer.  He was an early proponent of equal education rights for African Americans and women.  He advocated and expanded the Oratory systems of [[Fran\u00e7ois Delsarte]] and [[James Rush]].<ref>[[#Werner|Werner, Edgar S., 1898]], p. 200</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FCIxDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=greek+riots+kansas+city&source=bl&ots=qUG8pTlU4W&sig=ACfU3U0kuRlc4iHu8GmgyKU8JUEXPo7aNg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjiycD31OPnAhWFY8AKHUujCO04ChDoATACegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=zachos&f=false \"Peter C. Moskos\"] ''Greek Americans: Struggle and Success'' Routeledge 2017: p. 6</ref> \n\n==Early life==\n\nJohn Celivergos Zachos, was born in [[Constantinople]] now Istanbul Turkey. His parents were Nicholas and Euphrosyne Zachos. They were from Athens Greece. [[Nicholas Zachos]] was a general in the Greek army during the Greek Revolution.  Zachos died in 1824 during battle.  \n\n[[Samuel Gridley Howe]] an American Surgeon and [[Philhellene]] was also fighting for Greek independence.  He brought John Celivergos Zachos along with other young Greek people back to the United States to educate them.<ref name=\"beta\"> [https://books.google.com/books?id=OwITAAAAIAAJ&dq=Helena%20Zachos&pg=PA381#v=onepage&q=Helena%20Zachos&f=false \"Biography of John C. Zachos\"] ''Beta Theta Pi'' 25(April 1898): p. 381-382.</ref>\n\nNamely traveling with Zachos and Howe was a young refuge who survived the [[Chios massacre]] named [[Christophoros P. Kastanes]].  In 1851, he wrote a book on his travels called\n''The Greek Exile, Or, a Narrative of the Captivity and Escape of Christophorus Plato Castanis.'' This book includes John C. Zachos and other Greek children.<ref>[[#Modern| Kaloudis, George , 2018]], p. 31</ref><ref>[[#Kastanes| Kastanes, Christophoros P. , 2018]], p. 135</ref>\n\n==Education and Marriage==\n\nIn 1830, John Celivergos Zachos was in the United States.  He was placed in a Preliminary school in Amherst Massachusetts with [[Christophoros P. Kastanes]] and other greek children.<ref>[[#Kastanes| Kastanes, Christophoros P. , 2018]], p. 135</ref>  In 1836, he enrolled at [[Kenyon College]] in Gambier Ohio.  He graduated from the institution by 1840. As a young adult he was noted for fine speaking, he won prizes whenever he competed.  He was the founder of the Society of Kenyon College. <ref>[[#Modern| Kaloudis, George , 2018]], p. 31</ref><ref>[[#Werner|Werner, Edgar S., 1898]], p. 200</ref>\n\nHe went off to study medicine at [[Miami University]] in Oxford Ohio, he graduated in the mid eighteen forties.  When he finished his studies he moved to Cincinnati where he founded a Shakespearian Society.  He married Harriet Tompkins Canfield Zachos on July 26, 1849.<ref>[[#Family|Canfield, 1897]], p. 197 </ref>\n\nHarriet Tompkins was born on January 15, 1824 to George Washington Canfield and Catherine A Clark.  They had 6 children.  Born between 1850 to 1865. His daughter Mary [[Helena Zachos]] became an American college professor and elocutionist. <ref>[[#Family|Canfield, 1897]], p. 54 Chart 9 </ref>\n\n==Career & Later Life==\n \nIn the eighteen fifties John C. Zachos was well known locally as an [[elocution]]ist, he traveled around Ohio lecturing about literature at various institutions.  Zachos became associate dean at [[Antioch College]] which was in Yellow Springs Ohio.  He worked under his close friend [[Horace Mann]]. Mann was also associated with [[Samuel Gridley Howe]].  At [[Antioch College]] Zachos read Shakespeare and lectured courses on the English Poets.  \n\nIn 1862 he was the editor of the Ohio Journal.  During the outbreak of the civil war Zachos served under General [[Rufus Saxton]] as a surgeon for the Union Army. He was stationed at Paris Island South Carolina.  \nDuring the civil war he was commissioned by the New York and Boston educational society to demonstrate that African Americans were capable of acquiring knowledge.  He also educated them.  He is noted for writing and reciting poetry to the freed slaves.\n\n<div class=\"center\">\n''Ye sons of burning Afric's soil,''<br/>\n''Lift up your hands of hardened toil''<br/>\n''Your shouts from every hill recoil''<br/>\n''Today your are free''<ref>[[#Firebrand |Ash, Stephen V., 2008]], p. 19</ref></div>\n\n\nAfter 2 years of service in the Civil War he traveled to Boston where he became a Unitarian Minister.  He gave twelve lectures at the [[Lowell Institute]].  He began to gain notoriety as a Literature Professor in the east.  For 3 years he was Professor of Public Speech and Literature at the [[Meadville Lombard Theological School]].  While at the Theological School he established another Literary Society.    \nAmerican author, historian, and Unitarian minister [[Edward Everett Hale]] spoke very highly of John C. Zachos.<ref>[[#Werner|Werner, Edgar S., 1898]], p. 200</ref>\n\nIn 1871, now 51 he moved to New York City where he would stay until the time of his death.  [[Peter Cooper]] and John C. Zachos became good friends. \nZachos influenced the foundation of [[Cooper Union]].  He taught literature and public speech.  In 1876 he was Peter Cooper's first biographer.  He was a Professor and Library Curator at [[Cooper Union]].<ref>[[#Curator|U.S. Government, 1897]], p. 383</ref>\n\nOn December 24th, 1875 he filed patent number 175892 for type writers and phenotypic notation application.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0hEzAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1942&lpg=PA1942&dq=Patent+No.+175,892&source=bl&ots=tj_PL4pqlE&sig=ACfU3U2gKS_6OOFbxhA7WtVEINujNu_Y4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjou4a0gObnAhWrdN8KHeQjCdkQ6AEwBXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=Patent%20No.%20175%2C892&f=false \"The Commissioners of Patents' Journal\"] ''US Patent 175892'' (August 4 1876): p. 1942</ref> The machine was a stenotype used for printing legible English text at a high speed.  He obtained 10,000 dollars in investment capital for his invention.<ref>[[#Werner|Werner, Edgar S., 1898]], p. 201</ref>.  He continued his advancement of oratory the next two decades.\n\nHe was a proponent of the Delsarte System of Oratory founded by [[Fran\u00e7ois Delsarte]].  He also advocated the James Rush classic, ''The Philosophy of the Human Voice''.  James Rush was the son of [[Benjamin Rush]].<ref>{{cite web\n|url=  https://www.acsu.buffalo.edu/~duchan/new_history/hist19c/subpages/rush.html\n|title= A History of Speech - Language Pathology\n|publisher=S.U.N.Y University of Buffalo      \n|author=  Emeritus Professor Judith Felson Duchan\n|date=       May 11, 2011\n|accessdate= February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nZachos lectures were very popular at Cooper Union.  Namely on Tuesdays and Saturdays the crowd would exceed 100 to 200 people.  [[Peter Cooper]] told [[William Cullen Bryant]] to personally observe Professor Zachos lecture.  In \"The Letters of William Cullen Bryant\" Bryant called Zachos an oratory genius.<ref name=\"beta\" /><ref>[https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Letters_of_William_Cullen_Bryant/LhS9DwAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=John+Celivergos+Zachos&pg=PT214&printsec=frontcover \"William Cullen Bryant \"] ''The Letters of William Cullen Bryant Volume VI'' 1872\u20131878: Letter 2250</ref>   Due to his poetry lectures he also gained the recognition of [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]] and [[James Russell Lowell]].\n\nHis writing was not confined to literature.  Zachos also wrote about philosophy, mathematics, science, metaphysics and other scientific branches.  Under the pseudonym \"[[Cadmus]]\" Dr Zachos wrote about financial and economic subjects that were published in various New York City publications.   \n\nOn January 7, 1896 Harriet Tompkins Zachos passed away.  Roughly two years later on March 20, 1898, John Celivergos Zachos died.  His Funeral was held at the [[Church of the Messiah (Manhattan)]].  Among the many in attendance were his [[pallbearer]]s S. Packard, [[Augustus D. Juilliard]] Former NYC mayor [[William Lafayette Strong]] and Union army brevet brigadier general [[Henry Lawrence Burnett]].  At the time of his death his residence was 113 west 84th street New York City.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=W2s-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA587&dq=Samuel+Gridley+Howe+zachos&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU3JusmujnAhWimuAKHS3AC-k4FBDoATABegQIARAK#v=snippet&q=Samuel%20Gridley%20Howe%20zachos&f=false \"F. Leypoldt (1898)\"] ''The Publishers Weekly, Volume 53 No 1365'' W.M. Wood & CO., Publishers, New York p. 587</ref>\n\n==Literary Works==\n*''New American Speaker 1852''\n*''Elocution 1861''\n*''New System of Phonic Reading 1863\n*''Phonic Primer and Reader 1864''\n*''A Sketch of the Life and Opinions of Mr. Peter Cooper 1876,''\n*''The Political and Financial Opinions of Peter Cooper Edited by J.C. Zachos,''\n*''An Address to the Merchants and Professional Men of the Country, without Respect to Parties (1878)''\n*''The Fiscal Problem of All Civilized Nations (1881)''<ref>{{cite web\n|url=  https://onlinebooks.library.upenn.edu/webbin/book/lookupname?key=Zachos%2C%20J%2E%20C%2E%20%28John%20Celivergos%29%2C%201820%2D1898\n|title= The Online Books Page ''Online Books by J. C. Zachos''\n|publisher= University of Pennsylvania      \n|author=  John Mark Ockerbloom\n|date=       February 21, 2020\n|accessdate= February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Canfield |first=Fredreick A. |authorlink=Fredreick A Canfield |year=1897|title=A History of Thomas Canfield and of Matthew Camfield with A Genealogy of their Descendants in New Jersey |publisher=The Title Morehouse & Taylor Press, New Haven Conn |ref=Family |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EoY_AAAAYAAJ&pg=RA3-PA7&lpg=RA3-PA7&dq=Robert+H.+Zachos&source=bl&ots=jEEcTSH4X-&sig=ACfU3U2RNIj60gFjI4VYXCMk3X0AaeEPCA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil-8XotufnAhWQmnIEHSQ3B0cQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Robert%20H.%20Zachos&f=false}}\n* {{cite book |last=Government |first=U.S. |authorlink=U.S. Government |year=1897|title=\nArt and Industry: Industrial and technical training in voluntary associ